  <h2>First Steps, in Order</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Stop using water.</strong> No flushing, laundry, dishwasher or showers — every gallon you add makes the backup worse.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep people and pets away.</strong> Backed-up wastewater carries bacteria; wear gloves if you must be near it and keep children clear.</li>
    <li><strong>Don’t pour chemicals or drain cleaner in.</strong> They rarely clear a septic backup and can make the situation harder — and more hazardous — for whoever services it.</li>
    <li><strong>Note whether it’s one drain or the whole house.</strong> A single affected fixture may be a local clog; multiple or the lowest drains backing up points to the septic system itself.</li>
    <li><strong>Request service.</strong> A backup rarely resolves on its own and usually worsens — the sooner it’s evaluated, the better.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why Backups Happen</h2>
  <p>
    Knowing the usual causes helps you understand what a provider will check. A tank that is full
    has no room, so wastewater backs up. A blockage — roots, grease or a collapsed line — can stop
    flow between the house, tank and field. A drain field that can no longer absorb water pushes
    wastewater back through the system, which tends to be the more serious case. And sometimes a
    marginal system is simply overwhelmed by heavy use or by ground that is saturated after heavy
    rain. From inside the house these can look alike, which is why an on-site evaluation matters.
    The <a href="/resources/septic-repairs-drain-fields/">repairs and drain-fields hub</a> explains
    how these components are assessed.
  </p>

